IN SEPTEMBER, Daily Sun ran a story of a man who pretended to be North West Premier Supra Mahumapelo and defrauded people of money. On Wednesday, the fate of the fraudster who unlawfully and falsely demanded money from people was decided at the Mahikeng Regional Court in Mmabatho, North West. Thato Hangari was given a five-year sentence, suspended for three years on condition he is not convicted of an offence involving dishonesty during this period. if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>The 26-year-old man from Kuruman in the Northern Cape pleaded guilty to a charge of fraud and admitted to receiving money he was not entitled to. He admitted that he knew he was not acting on Mahumapelo’s instructions and that his actions were unlawful. Mahumapelo welcomed the sentence and voiced his confidence in the justice system. “This must be a lesson to the accused that crime does not pay. I am happy that the law has taken its course,” said the premier. The Hawks arrested Hengari in December after a Western Cape MP blew the whistle on him. A trap was set and he was bust near Kuruman.